article.description: The Miami Heat tried desperately to get back into the playoff race, and Ben Wallace got in their way.
article.headline: Wallace swats Mourning, keeps Heat out of race

images.name: Wallace_Ben 020402 inline
images.caption: Detroit's Ben Wallace grabs one of his game-high 16 rebounds.

article.linkText: Defensive guru Wallace stands in way of Heat
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- The Miami Heat tried desperately to get back into the playoff race, and Ben Wallace got in their way. The NBA leader in blocked shots rejected Alonzo Mourning with 15 seconds left to preserve the lead, and the Detroit Pistons beat the fading Heat 90-87 Tuesday night. Wallace finished with 16 rebounds and six blocks. "We've been priding ourselves on defense all season," Wallace said. "Tonight was a great example of that." The Pistons, who have won 15 of their past 18 road games, trail the New Jersey Nets for the Eastern Conference lead by two games with eight to go. Miami remained 11th in the East with nine games left, four games behind eighth-place Indiana in the race for the final playoff berth. The Heat failed to capitalize on a loss Tuesday by the Pacers. "The fact that somebody else is losing and we're not winning at home compounds it," Heat coach Pat Riley said. "It was a winnable game." The defeat dropped Miami to 32-41, assuring Riley of his first non-winning season in 20 years as an NBA coach. Detroit led by one when Mourning crossed the lane, appeared to shake defender Cliff Robinson and put up a hook shot. Wallace came from the weak side for the block. "He made a good play," Mourning said. "I had a good look. He pretty much made a play that I usually make." Wallace said Robinson's defense on Mourning helped. "Cliff made him come a little farther than he wanted to," Wallace said. "Cliff forced him to come into my airspace. It's a no-fly zone." Jerry Stackhouse made one of two free throws with 12 seconds remaining to put the Pistons up by two, and Miami's LaPhonso Ellis badly missed a 3-point try with 3 seconds left. "I got a good look," Ellis said. "I just didn't make it. I'm a 10-year veteran. I expect myself to make those shots." The Heat, who missed their final seven shots, lost for the sixth time in seven games. They're on the verge of missing the playoffs for the first time in seven years, and Riley could miss the postseason for the first time. Detroit had lost five straight games in Miami. Pistons reserve forward Corliss Williamson scored 20 points, and Chucky Atkins added 18 -- 16 in the second half. Stackhouse, held without a basket until midway through the third quarter, finished with 14. Wallace scored only four points but has totaled 89 rebounds in his past five games. Eddie Jones led Miami with 20 points. The Heat led by 10 points early, fell behind by six in the third period and pulled even at 69-all on a basket by Jones. Jon Barry's 3-pointer put Detroit ahead 79-75 before the Heat scored nine consecutive points, including a basket by Rod Strickland to put them ahead. The Pistons regained the lead, 86-85, on Robinson's 3-pointer with 1:50 to go. Jones made two free throws for Miami, but Atkins scored on a drive with 1:20 left to put the Pistons ahead 88-87.

Game notes
Detroit won the season series 2-1. Miami lost at Detroit on Dec. 30, which left the Heat 5-23. They won 24 of their next 34 games before beginning their late-season swoon. ... Miami is last in the NBA in scoring but first in scoring defense. ... The Pistons are 13-8 in games decided by four points or less. ... The Heat fell to 3-15 when trailing at home going into the fourth quarter.
